[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] These standards are specified in Clauses 125 and 126 of the IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The physical (PHY) layer transmission technology of IEEE 802.3bz is based on 10GBASE-T, but operates at a lower signaling rate.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] By reducing the original signal rate to 1⁄4 or 1⁄2, the link speed drops to 2.5 or 5 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The spectral bandwidth of the signal is reduced accordingly, lowering the requirements on the cabling, so that 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T can be deployed at a cable length of up to 100 m on Cat 5e or better cables.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The NBASE-T effort also standardized how its switches can implement power over Ethernet according to the IEEE 802.3at and successor standards.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] This allows a single cable to provide both power and data for high-bandwidth wireless access points such as those that implement the IEEE 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standards.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Prior to the release of 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T, manufacturers of wireless access points that wanted to support multi-gigabit uplink speed using standard gigabit Ethernet ports had to include multiple Ethernet ports on their access points.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] By bonding the connections from multiple Ethernet ports via IEEE 802.3ad link aggregation or similar, manufacturers were able to achieve speeds close to 2 Gbit/s by using two ports that support gigabit speeds.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] This would require the wireless access point to be connected to the rest of the network with 2 Ethernet cables and require both the wireless access point and network hardware to support and be configured for link aggregation.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Wireless access points that support 2.5GBASE-T or 5GBASE-T eliminate this complexity.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] In 2013 with the release of IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5), wireless access points for the first time could reach speeds of 2 Gbit/s or 4 Gbit/s, exceeding the 1 Gbit/s IEEE 802.3ab 1000BASE-T wired Ethernet uplink.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] While 10GBASE-T had already been standardized since 2006, this standard used a higher signaling frequency that would have substantially limited the maximum distance of Cat5e cable runs.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Therefore, there was demand for an intermediate standard that could uplink the 2 Gbit/s and 4 Gbit/s speeds from wireless access points over existing Cat5e cable.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The development of the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards enabled wireless access points to reach their maximum speeds without being limited by the Ethernet uplink speeds over a single existing Cat5e cable, while also being compatible with newer Cat6 and Cat6a cabling.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards also serve as an interim solution for achieving lower-cost and lower power consumption multi-gigabit network speeds.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] As of Dec 2022, 10GBASE-T network equipment is still substantially more expensive than 1GBASE-T, 2.5GBASE-T, and 5GBASE-T network equipment.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3bz also supports power over Ethernet, which had previously not been available with IEEE 802.3an 10GBASE-T.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] As early as 2013, the Intel Avoton server processors integrated 2.5 Gbit/s Ethernet ports.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Whilst Broadcom had announced a series of 2.5 Gbit/s transceiver ICs, 2.5 Gbit/s switch hardware was not widely commercially available at that point.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Many early 10GBASE-T switches, particularly those with SFP+ interfaces, do not support the intermediate speeds.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] In October 2014, the NBASE-T Alliance was founded, initially comprising Cisco, Aquantia, Freescale, and Xilinx.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] By December 2015, it contained more than 45 companies, and aimed to have its specification compatible with 802.3bz.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The competing MGBASE-T Alliance, stating the same faster Gigabit Ethernet objectives, was founded in December 2014.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] In contrast to NBASE-T, the MGBASE-T said that their specifications would be open source.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3's 2.5G/5GBASE-T Task Force started working on the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards in March 2015.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The two NBASE-T and MGBASE-T Alliances ended up collaborating. with the forming of the IEEE 802.3bz Task Force under the patronage of the Ethernet Alliance in June 2015.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] On September 23, 2016, the IEEE-SA Standards Board approved IEEE Std 802.3bz-2016.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3ch-2020 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 standards are derived from the IEEE 802.3bp-2016 1000BASE-T1 Ethernet over single twisted pair standard, and share very little in common with the similarly named 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards at the PHY layer.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 can run over a single twisted pair up to 15 meters in length, use PAM8 modulation (compared to PAM3 modulation in 1000BASE-T1 or PAM-16 + 128DSQ in 2.5GBASE-T/5GBASE-T), and are standardized in 802.3ch-2020.
[src:autosar-adaptive/automotive-ethernet] Their primary use is in embedded automotive applications, and are commonly referred to as part of the Automotive Ethernet family of standards, along with 100BASE-T1 and 1000BASE-T1.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The objectives are scalability to different vehicle and platform variants, transferability of software, consideration of availability and safety requirements, cooperation between different partners, sustainable use of natural resources and maintainability during the product lifecycle.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR was formed in July 2003 by Bavarian Motor Works (BMW), Robert Bosch GmbH, Continental AG, Mercedes-Benz Group AG, Siemens VDO and Volkswagen AG to develop and establish an open industry standard for the automotive electrical-electronic (E/E) architecture.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In November 2003, the Ford Motor Company joined as a Core Partner.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In the following December Peugeot Citroën Automobiles S.A. and the Toyota Motor Corporation followed.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In November of the following year, General Motors Holding LLC also joined as a Core Partner.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] After Siemens VDO was acquired by Continental in February 2008, Siemens VDO is no longer independently represented as a Core Partner of AUTOSAR.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Since 2003, AUTOSAR has provided four major versions of the standardized automotive software architecture for its Classic Platform and one release, along with the version of acceptance tests.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In 2013, the AUTOSAR consortium introduced a continuous working mode for the Classic Platform to maintain the standard and provide selected improvements (including releases R4.2, and 1.0 of acceptance tests).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In 2016, work began on the Adaptive Platform.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] An initial release (17-03) was published in early 2017, followed by release 17–10 in October 2017 and release 18–03 in March 2018.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] With release 18–10 in October 2018, the major development activities were published.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR aims to establish a global standard for software and methodology, enabling open E/E system architectures for future intelligent mobility.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] This vision focuses on ensuring high levels of dependability, particularly in terms of safety and security.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR provides specifications for basic software modules, defines application interfaces, and builds a common development methodology based on a standardized exchange format.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The basic software modules made available by the AUTOSAR layered software architecture can be used in vehicles from different manufacturers and electronic components from different suppliers, thereby reducing expenditures for research and development.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Based on this principle, AUTOSAR aims to prepare for upcoming technologies.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The motivation behind AUTOSAR is to manage the increasing complexity of software and E/E systems as their functional scope expands.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The initiative is designed to support flexibility in product modifications, upgrades, and updates, while leveraging scalable solutions within and across product lines.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Enhancing scalability and flexibility in the integration and transfer of functions is a key objective, aiming to improve the quality and reliability of software and E/E systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The goals of AUTOSAR include addressing future vehicle requirements such as availability, safety, software upgrades, updates, and maintainability.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR seeks to enhance scalability and flexibility for function integration and transfer.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Additionally, the initiative aims to increase the use of "Commercial off the Shelf" software and hardware components across product lines, promoting software reuse.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] By accelerating development and maintenance processes, AUTOSAR intends to improve the management of product and process complexity and risk, while optimizing the costs associated with scalable systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The purpose of the foundation standard is to enforce interoperability between the AUTOSAR platforms.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The foundation contains common requirements and technical specifications (for example protocols) shared between the AUTOSAR platforms, and the common methodology.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The AUTOSAR classic platform is the standard for embedded real-time ECUs based on OSEK.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The architecture distinguishes between three software layers that run on a microcontroller: application, runtime environment (RTE) and basic software (BSW).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The application software layer is mostly hardware independent.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Communication between software components and access to BSW happens via RTE, which represents the full interface for applications.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Services are divided further, into functional groups representing the infrastructure for system, memory and communication services.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] One essential concept of the Classic Platform is the Virtual Functional Bus (VFB).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] This virtual bus is an abstract set of RTEs that are not yet deployed to specific ECUs and decouples the applications from the infrastructure.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] It communicates via dedicated ports, which means that the communication interfaces of the application software must be mapped to these ports.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The VFB handles communication within the individual ECU and between ECUs.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] From an application point of view, no detailed knowledge of lower-level technologies or dependencies is required.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] This supports hardware-independent development and usage of application software.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The Classic Platform also enables the integration of non-AUTOSAR systems such as GENIVI, now renamed COVESA, by using the Franca Interface Definition Language (Franca IDL).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Standardization of functional interfaces across manufacturers and suppliers and standardization of the interfaces between the different software layers is seen as a basis for achieving the technical goals of AUTOSAR.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Only by standardizing concrete interface contents in their physical and temporal representation allows achieving the needed integration compatibility.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] New use-cases required the development of the adaptive platform.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] One example is automated driving, in the context of which the driver temporarily and/or partially transfers responsibility for driving to the vehicle.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Further, Car-2-X applications require interaction to vehicles and off-board systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] That means that the system has to provide secure on-board communication, support of cross-domain computing platforms, smartphone integration, integration of non-AUTOSAR systems, and so on.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Also, cloud-based services will require dedicated means for security, such as secure cloud interaction and emergency vehicle preemption.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] They will enable remote and distributed services, such as remote diagnostics, over the air (OTA) update, repair, and exchange handling.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] To support dynamic deployment of customer applications and to provide an environment for applications that require high-end computing power AUTOSAR is currently standardizing the AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Its core is an operating system based on the POSIX standard.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The operating system can be used by the application via a subset of the POSIX according to IEEE1003.13 (namely PSE51).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] One of the key features of the Adaptive Platform is service-oriented communication since the Platform is based on the Service - Oriented Architecture.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Adaptive AUTOSAR is developed and written using C++ which is an object-oriented programming language.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The communication protocol used for the in-vehicle networking is SOME/IP, based on Ethernet.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Two types of interfaces are available: services and application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The platform consists of functional clusters which are grouped in services and the AUTOSAR adaptive platform foundation.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Functional clusters in AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform have to have at least one instance per (virtual) machine while services may be distributed in the in-car network.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The adaptive platform contains both specification and code.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] In comparison to the Classic Platform, AUTOSAR develops an implementation to shorten the validation cycle and illustrate the underlying concepts.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] This implementation is available to all AUTOSAR partners.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR defined six different levels of membership.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Core Partners are since 2026 AUMOVIO (AUMOVIO Germany GmbH), BMW (BMW AG), Bosch (Robert Bosch GmbH), Denso, GM (General Motors Holding LLC), Huawei (Huawei Technologies Co.Ltd.), Mercedes-Benz (Mercedes-Benz Group AG), Toyota (TMC), Vector (Vector Informatik GmbH) and VW (Volkswagen AG).
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] These companies are responsible for organization, administration and control of the AUTOSAR development partnership.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Within this core, the executive board defines the overall strategy and roadmap.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The Steering Committee manages day-to-day non-technical operations and admission of partners, public relations and contractual issues.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The chairman and Deputy of chairman, appointed for one year, represent the Steering Committee for that purpose.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] The AUTOSAR Spokesperson takes over the communication with the outside world.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Premium Partner Plus companies support the project leader team in the various technical, organizational and everyday processes.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] They also give new strategic inputs to the project leader round.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Premium and Development members contribute to work packages coordinated and monitored by the Project Leader Team established by the Core Partners.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Associate partners are making use of the standard documents AUTOSAR has already released.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Attendees are currently participating with Academic collaboration and non-commercial projects.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Selection of vendors, including RTOS, BSW, design tools, compiler, etc.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Vendors which provide related tools and software, e.g. for testing, diagnostics, development, etc.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] AUTOSAR takes part in various events every year.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] Furthermore the AUTOSAR Open Conference (AOC) is planned every year to network and give an overview over the newest achievements.
[src:autosar-adaptive/autosar] A list of the events which are planned can be found on the AUTOSAR website.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:autosar-adaptive/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] In computing, **POSIX Threads**, commonly known as **pthreads** (after its header **<pthread.h>**), is an execution model that exists independently from a programming language, as well as a parallel execution model.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] It allows a program to control multiple different flows of work that overlap in time.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Each flow of work is referred to as a *thread*, and creation and control over these flows is achieved by making calls to the POSIX Threads API.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] POSIX Threads is an API defined by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard *POSIX.1c, Threads extensions (IEEE Std 1003.1c-1995)*.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Implementations of the API are available on many Unix-like POSIX-conformant operating systems such as FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Linux, macOS, Android, Solaris, Redox, QNX, and AUTOSAR Adaptive, typically bundled as a library **libpthread**.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] DR-DOS and Microsoft Windows implementations also exist: within the SFU/SUA subsystem which provides a native implementation of a number of POSIX APIs, and also within third-party packages such as *pthreads-w32*, which implements pthreads on top of existing Windows API.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] pthreads defines a set of C programming language types, functions and constants.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] It is implemented with a `pthread.h` header and a thread library.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] The POSIX semaphore API works with POSIX threads but is not part of the threads standard, having been defined in the *POSIX.1b, Real-time extensions (IEEE Std 1003.1b-1993)* standard.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Consequently, the semaphore procedures are prefixed by `sem_` instead of `pthread_`.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] This program creates five threads, each executing the function *perform_work* that prints the unique number of this thread to standard output.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] If a programmer wanted the threads to communicate with each other, this would require defining a variable outside of the scope of any of the functions, making it a global variable.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Here is one of the many possible outputs from running this program.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Windows does not support the pthreads standard natively; therefore, the Pthreads4w project seeks to provide a portable and open-source wrapper implementation.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] It can also be used to port Unix software (which uses pthreads) with little or no modification to the Windows platform.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Pthreads4w version 3.0.0 or later, released under the Apache Public License v2.0, is compatible with 64-bit or 32-bit Windows systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Version 2.11.0, released under the LGPLv3 license, is also 64-bit or 32-bit compatible.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] The Mingw-w64 project also contains a wrapper implementation of 'pthreads, **winpthreads**, which tries to use more native system calls than the Pthreads4w project.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix-threads] Interix environment subsystem available in the Windows Services for UNIX/Subsystem for UNIX-based Applications package provides a native port of the pthreads API, i.e. not mapped on Win32 API but built directly on the operating system syscall interface.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The **Portable Operating System Interface** (**POSIX**; IPA: /ˈpɒz.ɪks/) is a family of standards specified by the IEEE Computer Society for maintaining compatibility between operating systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] In order to define a level of compatibility, POSIX specifies many aspects of functionality that can be classified as application programming interface (API), command-line shell, and shell commands.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Originally derived from commonly-found Unix APIs, shells, and commands (partly because Unix was considered manufacturer-neutral), today many systems conform to the standard – including branded Unix systems, Unix-like systems, and many systems that were historically unrelated to Unix.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The standardized user command line and scripting interface were based on the UNIX System V Bourne shell.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Many user-level programs, services, and utilities (including awk, echo, ed) were also standardized, based on UNIX System V versions of them, along with required program-level services (including basic I/O: file, terminal, and network).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] POSIX also defines a standard threading library API which is supported by most modern operating systems.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The POSIX standard is developed by the Austin Group (a joint working group among the IEEE, The Open Group, and the ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22/WG 15).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] POSIX is intended to be used by both application and system developers.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The standards emerged from a project that began in 1984 building on work from related activity in the */usr/group* association.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Richard Stallman suggested the name *POSIX* to the IEEE instead of the former *IEEE-IX*.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The committee found it more easily pronounceable and memorable, and thus adopted it.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Originally, POSIX referred to IEEE Std 1003.1-1988, released in 1988.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The family of POSIX standards is formally designated as **IEEE 1003** and the ISO/IEC standard number is ISO/IEC 9945.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] POSIX originally consisted of a single document for core services but over time additional documents were published to extend and revise the specification.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Before 1997, POSIX comprised multiple documents that were published over the course of several years.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] After 1997, the Austin Group produces specifications titled Single UNIX Specification (SUS).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Over time, the group publishes versions of this specification and later POSIX is amended per some or all of a SUS version.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] A SUS version consists of a collection of volumes – each for a grouping of required behavior – plus other information (outside of a volume).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Each volume is assigned an issue number that is the same for each volume of a version, but is not the same value as the version.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] For example, SUS version 3 (SUSv3) includes volumes labeled issue 6.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] IEEE Std 1003.1-2004 modifies POSIX.1-2001 via two minor updates or errata referred to as technical corrigenda documents.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Similar to its predecessor, POSIX.1-2008 (*IEEE Std 1003.1-2008*, 2016 Edition) consists of most of the normative material of SUSv4 (issue 7 of volumes *Base Definitions*, *System Interfaces and Headers*, *Commands and Utilities*).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] SUSv4 also includes rationale information that largely applies to POSIX although not included per se.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] As of POSIX 2024, the standard is aligned with the C17 language standard.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] POSIX mandates 512-byte default block sizes for the df and du utilities, reflecting the typical size of blocks on disks.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] When Richard Stallman and the GNU team were implementing POSIX for the GNU operating system, they objected to this on the grounds that most people think in terms of 1024 byte (or 1 KiB) blocks.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The environment variable POSIX_ME_HARDER was introduced to allow the user to force the standards-compliant behaviour.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The variable name was later changed to POSIXLY_CORRECT.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] As of 2025, this variable is also used for a number of other behaviour quirks.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] An operating system can be classified depending upon the degree of conformance with a POSIX standard.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Current versions of the following operating systems have been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests and their certification has not expired and the operating system has not been discontinued.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Some versions of the following operating systems had been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The certification has expired and some of the operating systems have been discontinued.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The following operating systems are not certified as POSIX conformant, but they conform in large part to the standard by implementing POSIX support via a compatibility feature (usually translation libraries, or a layer atop the kernel).
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Some technologies allow an operating system to enjoy a level of conformance to POSIX even though the operating system itself has little or no conformance.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] Although Windows does not conform to POSIX, the following technologies provide a level of compliance.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] A lightweight implementation that has POSIX-compatible header files that map POSIX APIs to call their Windows API counterparts.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] An optional Windows subsystem included in Windows NT-based operating systems up to Windows 2000.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] A compatibility layer for running Linux binary executables natively on Windows 10 and 11 using a Linux image such as Ubuntu, Debian, or OpenSUSE among others, acting as an upgrade and replacement for Windows Services for UNIX.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] The first distribution available was Ubuntu.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] From AT&T Research implements a POSIX layer on top of the Win32 APIs.
[src:autosar-adaptive/posix] although the support remains largely incomplete and not fully interoperable with POSIX-compliant implementations.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:autosar-adaptive/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
